# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mesh-shaders
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] In computer graphics, a **shader** is a programmable operation which is applied to data as it moves through the rendering pipeline.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Shaders act on data such as vertices and primitives, generate or morph geometries and fragments, and calculate the colors in a rendered image.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Shaders can execute a wide variety of operations.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] In modern real-time computer graphics, shaders are run on graphics processing units (GPUs) - dedicated hardware which provide parallel execution of programs.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Because image rendering is an embarrassingly parallel problem (having an Amdahl's index of one), shaders benefit greatly from parallel computing, such as SIMD hardware.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] The drive for faster rendering has produced highly parallel processors, like GPUs, which are now used for general-purpose computing.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Shaders used for general purposes are commonly called *compute shaders*.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] The term "shader" was first introduced to the public by Pixar with version 3.0 of their RenderMan Interface Specification, originally published in May 1988.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] As graphics processing units evolved, major graphics software libraries such as OpenGL and Direct3D began to support shaders.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] The first shader-capable GPUs only supported pixel shading, but vertex shaders were quickly introduced once developers realized the power of shaders.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] The first video card with a programmable pixel shader was the Nvidia GeForce 3 (NV20), released in 2001.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Geometry shaders were introduced with Direct3D 10 and OpenGL 3.2.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Graphics hardware evolved toward a unified shader model, making all shaders equal.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] The traditional use of shaders is to operate on data in the graphics pipeline to control the rendering of an image.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Graphics shaders are classified according to their position in the pipeline, the data being manipulated, and the graphics API being used.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Vertex shaders are run once for each 3D vertex given to the graphics processor.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] The purpose is to transform each vertex's 3D position in virtual space to the 2D coordinate at which it appears on the screen (as well as a depth value for the Z-buffer).
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Vertex shaders can manipulate properties such as position, color and texture coordinates, but cannot create new vertices.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] The output of the vertex shader goes to the next stage in the pipeline, which is either a geometry shader if present, or the rasterizer.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Vertex shaders can enable powerful control over the details of position, movement, lighting, and color in any scene involving 3D models.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Geometry shaders were introduced in Direct3D 10 and OpenGL 3.2; formerly available in OpenGL 2.0+ with the use of extensions.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] This type of shader can generate new graphics primitives, such as points, lines, and triangles, from those primitives that were sent to the beginning of the graphics pipeline.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Geometry shader programs are executed after vertex shaders.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] They take as input a whole primitive, possibly with adjacency information.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] For example, when operating on triangles, the three vertices are the geometry shader's input.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] The shader can then emit zero or more primitives, which are rasterized and their fragments ultimately passed to a pixel shader.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Typical uses of a geometry shader include point sprite generation, geometry tessellation, shadow volume extrusion, and single pass rendering to a cube map.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] A typical real-world example of the benefits of geometry shaders would be automatic mesh complexity modification.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] A series of line strips representing control points for a curve are passed to the geometry shader and depending on the complexity required the shader can automatically generate extra lines each of which provides a better approximation of a curve.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] model rendered using fragment shaders with different outputs: solid white, applied texture, physically based shading.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Fragment shaders, also known as **pixel shaders**, compute color and other attributes of each "fragment": a unit of rendering work affecting at most a single output pixel.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] The simplest kinds of pixel shaders output one screen pixel as a color value; more complex shaders with multiple inputs/outputs are also possible.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Pixel shaders range from simply always outputting the same color, to applying a lighting value, to doing bump mapping, shadows, specular highlights, translucency and other phenomena.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] They can alter the depth of the fragment (for Z-buffering), or output more than one color if multiple render targets are active.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] In 3D graphics, a pixel shader alone cannot produce some kinds of complex effects because it operates only on a single fragment, without knowledge of a scene's geometry (i.e. vertex data).
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] However, pixel shaders do have knowledge of the screen coordinate being drawn, and can sample the screen and nearby pixels if the contents of the entire screen are passed as a texture to the shader.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] This technique can enable a wide variety of two-dimensional postprocessing effects such as blur, or edge detection/enhancement for cartoon/cel shaders.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Pixel shaders may also be applied in *intermediate* stages to any two-dimensional images—sprites or textures—in the pipeline, whereas vertex shaders always require a 3D scene.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] For instance, a pixel shader is the only kind of shader that can act as a postprocessor or filter for a video stream after it has been rasterized.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] OpenGL 4.0 and Direct3D 11 introduced a new shader class called a tessellation shader.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] The function can be related to a variety of variables, most notably the distance from the viewing camera to allow active level-of-detail scaling.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] This allows objects close to the camera to have fine detail, while further away ones can have more coarse meshes, yet seem comparable in quality.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] It also can drastically reduce required mesh bandwidth by allowing meshes to be refined once inside the shader units instead of down-sampling very complex ones from memory.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Some algorithms can up-sample any arbitrary mesh, while others allow for "hinting" in meshes to dictate the most characteristic vertices and edges.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Circa 2017, the AMD Vega microarchitecture added support for a new shader stage—primitive shaders—somewhat akin to compute shaders with access to the data necessary to process geometry.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Nvidia introduced mesh and task shaders with its Turing microarchitecture in 2018 which are also modelled after compute shaders.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Nvidia Turing is the world's first GPU microarchitecture that supports mesh shading through DirectX 12 Ultimate API, several months before Ampere RTX 30 series was released.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] In 2020, AMD and Nvidia released RDNA 2 and Ampere microarchitectures which both support mesh shading through DirectX 12 Ultimate.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] These mesh shaders allow the GPU to handle more complex algorithms, offloading more work from the CPU to the GPU, and in algorithm intense rendering, increasing the frame rate of or number of triangles in a scene by an order of magnitude.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Intel announced that Intel Arc Alchemist GPUs shipping in Q1 2022 will support mesh shaders.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Ray tracing shaders are supported by Microsoft via DirectX Raytracing, by Khronos Group via Vulkan, GLSL, and SPIR-V, by Apple via Metal.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Nvidia and AMD called the parts of the hardware responsible for executing these shaders "ray tracing cores".
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Compute kernels are routines compiled for high throughput accelerators (such as graphics processing units (GPUs), digital signal processors (DSPs), or field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs)), separate from but used by a main program (typically running on a central processing unit).
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] They may be specified by a separate programming language such as "OpenCL C", as "compute shaders" written in a shading language, or embedded directly in application code written in a high level language.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Compute kernels roughly correspond to inner loops when implementing algorithms in traditional languages (except there is no implied sequential operation), or to code passed to internal iterators.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Microsoft support this as DirectCompute.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] This single program, multiple data programming paradigm maps well to vector processors: there is an assumption that each invocation of a kernel within a batch is independent, allowing for data parallel execution.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] However, atomic operations may sometimes be used for synchronization between elements (for interdependent work), in some scenarios.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Individual invocations are given indices (in 1 or more dimensions) from which arbitrary addressing of buffer data may be performed (including scatter gather operations), so long as the non-overlapping assumption is respected.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] The Vulkan API provides the intermediate SPIR-V representation to describe *both* graphical shaders, and compute kernels in a language independent and machine independent manner.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] The intention is to facilitate language evolution and provide a more natural ability to leverage GPU compute capabilities, in line with hardware developments such as Unified Memory Architecture and Heterogeneous System Architecture.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] This allows closer cooperation between a CPU and GPU.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Much work has been done in the field of Kernel generation through LLMs as a means of optimizing code.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] KernelBench, created by the Scaling Intelligence Lab at Stanford, provides a framework to evaluate the ability of LLMs to generate efficient GPU kernels.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Cognition has created Kevin 32-B to create efficient CUDA kernels which is currently the highest performing model on KernelBench.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Tensor shaders are accelerator programs that deal with matrix operations on large arrays, a type of operation commonly used in neural network-based AI.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Tensor shaders are supported by Microsoft via DirectML, by Khronos Group via OpenVX, by Apple via Core ML, by Google via TensorFlow, by Linux Foundation via ONNX.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Nvidia and AMD called the parts of the hardware responsible for executing these shaders "tensor cores".
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Several programming languages exist specifically for writing shaders, and which is used can depend on the target environment.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] The shading language for OpenGL is GLSL, and Direct3D uses HLSL.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] The Metal framework, used by Apple devices, has its own shading language called Metal Shading Language.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Increasingly in modern graphics APIs, shaders are compiled into SPIR-V, an intermediate language, before they are distributed to the end user.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] This standard allows more flexible choice of shading language, regardless of target platform.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] First supported by Vulkan and OpenGL, SPIR-V is also being adopted by Direct3D.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] The graph is then compiled into a shader.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] In web development contexts, visual and component-based shader tools have also emerged.
[src:mesh-shaders/geometry-shader] Platforms such as shaders.com provide component-driven composition of shaders for integration into frontend frameworks including Vue, React, and Svelte, while tools such as Shadertoy and FragCoord.xyz focus on lower-level shader authoring and debugging.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] In 3D computer graphics and solid modeling, a **polygon mesh** is a collection of **vertices**, **edges** and **faces** that define the shape of a polyhedral object's surface.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] It simplifies rendering, as in a wire-frame model.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] The faces usually consist of triangles (triangle mesh), quadrilaterals (quads), or other simple convex polygons (n-gons).
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] A polygonal mesh may also be more generally composed of concave polygons, or even polygons with holes.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] The study of polygon meshes is a large sub-field of computer graphics (specifically 3D computer graphics) and geometric modeling.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Different representations of polygon meshes are used for different applications and goals.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] The variety of operations performed on meshes includes Boolean logic (Constructive solid geometry), smoothing, and simplification.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Algorithms also exist for ray tracing, collision detection, and rigid-body dynamics with polygon meshes.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] If the mesh's edges are rendered instead of the faces, then the model becomes a wireframe model.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Several methods exist for mesh generation, including the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Volumetric meshes are distinct from polygon meshes in that they explicitly represent both the surface and interior region of a structure, while polygon meshes only explicitly represent the surface (the volume is implicit).
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Objects created with polygon meshes must store different types of elements.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] These include vertices, edges, faces, polygons and surfaces.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] In many applications, only vertices, edges and either faces or polygons are stored.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] A renderer may support only 3-sided faces, so polygons must be constructed of many of these, as shown above.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] However, many renderers either support quads and higher-sided polygons, or are able to convert polygons to triangles on the fly, making it unnecessary to store a mesh in a triangulated form.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] A vertex in computer graphics terms is a data structure that describes the position of a point in 2, 3 or 4D space on a surface along with optional attributes - other values used to render the object correctly.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Most attributes of a vertex represent vectors in the space to be rendered.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] These vectors are typically 2 (*x, y*) or 3 (*x, y, z*) dimensional and can include a fourth homogeneous coordinate (*w*)..
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] In real-time rendering these properties are used by a vertex shader or vertex pipeline.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Attributes can include position, color, reflectance, specularity, texture mapping coordinates, normal vectors, and displacement mapping.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Polygon meshes may be represented in a variety of ways, using different methods to store the vertex, edge and face data.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Each representation has advantages and disadvantages, discussed in Smith (2006).
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes represent an object as a set of vertices connected to other vertices.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] This is the simplest representation, but not widely used since the face and edge information is implicit.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Thus, it is necessary to traverse the data in order to generate a list of faces for rendering.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] In addition, operations on edges and faces are not easily accomplished.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] However, VV meshes benefit from small storage space and efficient morphing of shape.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows a four-sided box as represented by a VV mesh.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Each vertex indexes its neighboring vertices.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] The last two vertices, 8 and 9 at the top and bottom center of the "box-cylinder", have four connected vertices rather than five.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] A general system must be able to handle an arbitrary number of vertices connected to any given vertex.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] For a complete description of VV meshes see Smith (2006).
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Face-vertex meshes represent an object as a set of faces and a set of vertices.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] This is the most widely used mesh representation, being the input typically accepted by modern graphics hardware.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Face-vertex meshes improve on VV mesh for modelling in that they allow explicit lookup of the vertices of a face, and the faces surrounding a vertex.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows the "box-cylinder" example as an FV mesh.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Vertex v5 is highlighted to show the faces that surround it.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Notice that, in this example, every face is required to have exactly 3 vertices.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] However, this does not mean every vertex has the same number of surrounding faces.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] For rendering, the face list is usually transmitted to the GPU as a set of indices to vertices, and the vertices are sent as position/color/normal structures (in the figure, only position is given).
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] This has the benefit that changes in shape, but not geometry, can be dynamically updated by simply resending the vertex data without updating the face connectivity.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Modelling requires easy traversal of all structures.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] With face-vertex meshes it is easy to find the vertices of a face.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Also, the vertex list contains a list of faces connected to each vertex.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Unlike VV meshes, both faces and vertices are explicit, so locating neighboring faces and vertices is constant time.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] However, the edges are implicit, so a search is still needed to find all the faces surrounding a given face.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Other dynamic operations, such as splitting or merging a face, are also difficult with face-vertex meshes.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Introduced by Baumgart in 1975, winged-edge meshes explicitly represent the vertices, faces, and edges of a mesh.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] This representation is widely used in modelling programs to provide the greatest flexibility in dynamically changing the mesh geometry, because split and merge operations can be done quickly.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Their primary drawback is large storage requirements and increased complexity due to maintaining many indices.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] A good discussion of implementation issues of Winged-edge meshes may be found in the book *Graphics Gems II*.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes address the issue of traversing from edge to edge, and providing an ordered set of faces around an edge.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] For any given edge, the number of outgoing edges may be arbitrary.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] To simplify this, winged-edge meshes provide only four, the nearest clockwise and counter-clockwise edges at each end.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] The other edges may be traversed incrementally.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] The information for each edge therefore resembles a butterfly, hence "winged-edge" meshes.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows the "box-cylinder" as a winged-edge mesh.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] The total data for an edge consists of 2 vertices (endpoints), 2 faces (on each side), and 4 edges (winged-edge).
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Rendering of winged-edge meshes for graphics hardware requires generating a face index list, which is usually done only when the geometry changes.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes are ideally suited for dynamic geometry, such as subdivision surfaces and interactive modelling, since changes to the mesh can occur locally.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Traversal across the mesh, as might be needed for collision detection, can be accomplished efficiently.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes are not the only representation which allows for dynamic changes to geometry.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] A representation which combines winged-edge meshes and face-vertex meshes is the render dynamic mesh (RDM), which explicitly stores both, the vertices of a face and faces of a vertex (like FV meshes), and the faces and vertices of an edge (like winged-edge).
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] RDM's require less storage space than standard winged-edge meshes, and can be directly rendered by graphics hardware since the face list contains an index of vertices.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] In addition, traversal from vertex to face is explicit (constant time), as is from face to vertex.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] RDM's do not require the four outgoing edges since these can be found by traversing from edge to face, then face to neighboring edge.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] RDM's benefit from the features of winged-edge meshes by allowing for geometry to be dynamically updated.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] See Tobler & Maierhofer (WSCG 2006) for more details.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] The notation *avg(V,V)* means the average number of vertices connected to a given vertex; *avg(E,V)* means the average number of edges connected to a given vertex, and *avg(F,V)* is the average number of faces connected to a given vertex.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] The notation "V → f1, f2, f3, ... → v1, v2, v3, ..." describes that a traversal across multiple elements is required to perform the operation.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] For example, to get "all vertices around a given vertex V" using the face-vertex mesh, it is necessary to first find the faces around the given vertex V using the vertex list.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Then, from those faces, use the face list to find the vertices around them.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes explicitly store nearly all information, and other operations always traverse to the edge first to get additional info.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes are the only representation that explicitly stores the neighboring vertices of a given vertex.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] As the mesh representations become more complex (from left to right in the summary), the amount of information explicitly stored increases.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] This gives more direct, constant time, access to traversal and topology of various elements but at the cost of increased overhead and space in maintaining indices properly.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] As a general rule, face-vertex meshes are used whenever an object must be rendered on graphics hardware that does not change geometry (connectivity), but may deform or morph shape (vertex positions) such as real-time rendering of static or morphing objects.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge or render dynamic meshes are used when the geometry changes, such as in interactive modeling packages or for computing subdivision surfaces.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes are ideal for efficient, complex changes in geometry or topology so long as hardware rendering is not of concern.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Streaming meshes store faces in an ordered, yet independent, way so that the mesh can be transmitted in pieces.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] The order of faces may be spatial, spectral, or based on other properties of the mesh.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Streaming meshes allow a very large mesh to be rendered even while it is still being loaded.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Progressive meshes transmit the vertex and face data with increasing levels of detail.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Unlike *streaming meshes*, progressive meshes give the overall shape of the entire object, but at a low level of detail.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Additional data, new edges and faces, progressively increase the detail of the mesh.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Normal meshes transmit progressive changes to a mesh as a set of normal displacements from a base mesh.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] With this technique, a series of textures represent the desired incremental modifications.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Normal meshes are compact, since only a single scalar value is needed to express displacement.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] However, the technique requires a complex series of transformations to create the displacement textures.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] There exist many different file formats for storing polygon mesh data.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Each format is most effective when used for the purpose intended by its creator.
[src:mesh-shaders/polygon-mesh] Popular formats include .fbx, .dae, .obj, and .stl.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] In vector computer graphics, CAD systems, and geographic information systems, a **geometric primitive** (or **prim**) is the simplest (i.e.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] 'atomic' or irreducible) geometric shape that the system can handle (draw, store).
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] Sometimes the subroutines that draw the corresponding objects are called "geometric primitives" as well.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] The most "primitive" primitives are point and straight line segments, which were all that early vector graphics systems had.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] In constructive solid geometry, primitives are simple geometric shapes such as a cube, cylinder, sphere, cone, pyramid, torus.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] Modern 2D computer graphics systems may operate with primitives which are curves (segments of straight lines, circles and more complicated curves), as well as shapes (boxes, arbitrary polygons, circles).
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] A common set of two-dimensional primitives includes lines, points, and polygons, although some people prefer to consider triangles primitives, because every polygon can be constructed from triangles (polygon triangulation).
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] All other graphic elements are built up from these primitives.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] In three dimensions, triangles or polygons positioned in three-dimensional space can be used as primitives to model more complex 3D forms.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] In some cases, curves (such as Bézier curves, circles, etc.) may be considered primitives; in other cases, curves are complex forms created from many straight, primitive shapes.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] In GIS, the terrain surface is often spoken of colloquially as "2 1/2 dimensional," because only the upper surface needs to be represented.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] Thus, elevation can be conceptualized as a scalar field property or function of two-dimensional space, affording it a number of data modeling efficiencies over true 3-dimensional objects.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] A shape of any of these dimensions greater than zero consists of an infinite number of distinct points.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] Because digital systems are finite, only a sample set of the points in a shape can be stored.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] Thus, vector data structures typically represent geometric primitives using a strategic sample, organized in structures that facilitate the software interpolating the remainder of the shape at the time of analysis or display, using the algorithms of Computational geometry.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] A wide variety of vector data structures and formats have been developed during the history of Geographic information systems, but they share a fundamental basis of storing a core set of geometric primitives to represent the location and extent of geographic phenomena.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] Locations of points are almost always measured within a standard Earth-based coordinate system, whether the spherical Geographic coordinate system (latitude/longitude), or a planar coordinate system, such as the Universal Transverse Mercator.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] They also share the need to store a set of attributes of each geographic feature alongside its shape; traditionally, this has been accomplished using the data models, data formats, and even software of relational databases.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] Early vector formats, such as POLYVRT, the ARC/INFO Coverage, and the Esri shapefile support a basic set of geometric primitives: points, polylines, and polygons, only in two dimensional space and the latter two with only straight line interpolation.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] TIN data structures for representing terrain surfaces as triangle meshes were also added.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] Since the mid 1990s, new formats have been developed that extend the range of available primitives, generally standardized by the Open Geospatial Consortium's Simple Features specification.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] Frequently, a representation of the shape of a real-world phenomenon may have a different (usually lower) dimension than the phenomenon being represented.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] For example, a city (a two-dimensional region) may be represented as a point, or a road (a three-dimensional volume of material) may be represented as a line.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] This dimensional generalization correlates with tendencies in spatial cognition.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] For example, asking the distance between two cities presumes a conceptual model of the cities as points, while giving directions involving travel "up," "down," or "along" a road imply a one-dimensional conceptual model.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] In CAD software or 3D modelling, the interface may present the user with the ability to create primitives which may be further modified by edits.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] For example, in the practice of box modelling the user will start with a cuboid, then use extrusion and other operations to create the model.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] In this use the primitive is just a convenient starting point, rather than the fundamental unit of modelling.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] A 3D package may also include a list of extended primitives which are more complex shapes that come with the package.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] For example, a teapot is listed as a primitive in 3D Studio Max.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] Various graphics accelerators exist with hardware acceleration for rendering specific primitives such as lines or triangles, frequently with texture mapping and shaders.
[src:mesh-shaders/primitive-geometry] Modern 3D accelerators typically accept sequences of triangles as triangle strips.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] In computer graphics, **rasterisation** (British English) or **rasterization** (American English) is the task of taking an image described in a vector graphics format (shapes) and converting it into a raster image which represents the original image.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] The rasterized image may then be displayed on a computer display, video display or printer, or stored in a bitmap file format.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] Rasterization may refer to the technique of drawing 3D models, or to the conversion of 2D rendering primitives, such as polygons and line segments, into a rasterized format.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] The term "rasterisation" comes from German *Raster* 'grid, pattern, schema' and Latin *rāstrum* 'scraper, rake'.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] Bresenham's line algorithm is an example of an algorithm used to rasterize lines.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] Algorithms such as the midpoint circle algorithm are used to render circles onto a pixelated canvas.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] Polygons are a common representation of digital 3D models.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] Before rasterization, individual polygons are triangulated - therefore, a typical problem to solve in 3D rasterization is rasterization of a triangle.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] 2. no pixel is rasterized more than once, i.e. the rasterized triangles don't overlap.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] This is to guarantee that the result doesn't depend on the order in which the triangles are rasterized.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] Overdrawing pixels can also mean wasting computing power on pixels that would be overwritten.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] This leads to establishing **rasterization rules** to guarantee the above conditions.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] 2. its center lies exactly on the triangle edge (or multiple edges in case of corners) – that is (or, in case of corners, all are), either the *top* or *left* edge.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] A *top* edge is an edge that is exactly horizontal and lies above other edges, and a *left* edge is a non-horizontal edge that is on the left side of the triangle.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] This rule decides which triangle a pixel on a boundary belongs to.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] It is implemented by Direct3D and OpenGL (although the specification here only requires a consistent rule).
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] Rasterization is one of the typical techniques of rendering 3D models.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] Compared with other rendering techniques such as ray tracing, rasterization is extremely fast and therefore used in most realtime 3D engines.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] However, rasterization is simply the process of computing the mapping from scene geometry to pixels and does not prescribe a particular way to compute the color of those pixels.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] The specific color of each pixel is assigned by a pixel shader (which in modern GPUs is completely programmable).
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] Shading may take into account physical effects such as light position, their approximations or purely artistic intent.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] The process of rasterizing 3D models onto a 2D plane for display on a computer screen ("screen space") is often carried out by fixed function (non-programmable) hardware within the graphics pipeline.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] This is because there is no motivation for modifying the techniques for rasterization used at render time and a special-purpose system allows for high efficiency.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] The quality of rasterization can be improved by antialiasing, which creates "smooth" edges.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] Sub-pixel precision is a method which takes into account positions on a finer scale than the pixel grid and can produce different results even if the endpoints of a primitive fall into same pixel coordinates, producing smoother movement animations.
[src:mesh-shaders/rasterisation] Simple or older hardware, such as PlayStation 1, lacked sub-pixel precision in 3D rasterization.
